1. e4 {This chapter
explores the Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit (3...f5), along with its sister, the
delayed Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit (3...a6 4. Ba4 f5). This is perhaps the
most concrete and theoretically testing chapter, in the sense that the lines
are often long and somewhat engine-like. But, if we know some stuff, we can
obtain a nice advantage, often even having an extra pawn.   Here is the
breakdown of the theory to know: 
___________________________________________________ The critical decision for
black is if they play:  5...d5 - which enters a sharp and tactical game, where
we retain a strong advantage 5...Nf6 - which is more solid and secure, but as
White we also need to know less theory and have somewhat less risk.   Within
those two variations, there is a smaller split later on. For organization’s
sake, I will quickly list that split here as well:   5...d5 splits into: (1) 7.
..Qd5 (we forcefully enter into a good endgame for White with queens off) (2)
and 7...Qg5 (the main move, where with accurate play we should win a pawn!)  5.
..Nf6 splits into:  (1) 9...Bg7 (an interesting pawn sac which we respond to
with a novelty from the computer which I am very fond of) (2) 9...e4 (a
combative move, which does not address the issues of the unsafe Black king,
and we try to quickly highlight this).} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 ( 3... a6 4. Ba4 f5 {We now look at the delayed Jaenisch/Schliemann Gambit, which is a worse
version of the normal f5 gambit, because of our extra option: d4.} 5. d4 fxe4 ( 5... exd4 6. e5 b5 7. Bb3 Na5 8. Qxd4 Nxb3 9. axb3 Ne7 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Qf4 ) 6. Nxe5 Nf6 7. O-O {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc1g5,Gf1e1]} ) 4. Nc3 ( 4. d4 {For illustrative
purposes-- to show the difference between the delayed and normal Jaenisch/
Schliemann Gambit} fxe4 5. Nxe5 Nxe5 6. dxe5 c6 {[%cal Gd8a5,Ga5e5]} ) 4... fxe4 {The only critical try: All other moves can be strongly met by exf5 (although
sometimes even better options exist).} ( 4... Nf6 5. exf5 ) ( 4... Bb4 5. exf5 ) ( 4... Nd4 5. exf5 {we have better moves, but for consistency, even taking on f5
is good here!} ) ( 4... Bc5 5. exf5 ) ( 4... d6 5. exf5 {we have better moves, but
for consistency, even taking on f5 is good here!} ) 5. Nxe4 {The first major
split: They can either play d5, or Nf6 -- In both cases, Black must target our
active central knight instantly.} d5 ( 5... Nf6 {This line is slightly less
popular, but engine approved. It makes sense, Black still targets our Knight,
but in a less reckless manner, and aims to finish development & castle.} 6. Qe2 d5 7. Nxf6+ gxf6 8. d4 {We have so much pressure on e4, that they can not
defend it. Now, Black has two options: push it forward to keep it alive, or
gambit it with Bg7.} e4 ( 8... Bg7 9. dxe5 O-O 10. O-O Nxe5 {Black has a major
threat here: Bg4. We need to stop it. h3 is a fine way to do so, but the
engine proposes an even more cunning idea, which is not too intuitive. Qd1, to
allow Be2. We consolidate our pieces and enable good coordination. Black's
initiative soon runs out of steam.  One extra piece of advise to remember:
unless for a very specific and solid reason, do NOT take on e5 and fix Black's
pawns, and open their rook.} ( 10... fxe5 11. Bxc6 bxc6 ( 11... e4 12. Bxd5+ Qxd5 13. Ng5 ) 12. Nxe5 ) 11. Qd1 c6 12. Be2 Bg4 ( 12... Qd6 13. c3 Be6 14. Re1 Rae8 15. Be3 ) 13. Nd4 Bxe2 14. Qxe2 ) 9. Nh4 {Black needs to watch over the f7
square, and can thus either play Qe7, or Be6.  To both of those moves, we need
to develop and castle, and look to break quickly with f3.} Be6 ( 9... Qe7 10. O-O Bd7 {The pin is broken, so be careful about playing f3. We have two
pleasant options. Play c3, then f3, or play Qh5 to go into a better endgame.} 11. c3 {Option 1 (c3 and f3 is what I like!)} ( 11. Qh5+ {I will show option 2,
though option 1 is just as good.} Qf7 12. Qxf7+ Kxf7 13. Be3 ) 11... O-O-O 12. f3 ) 10. O-O Qd7 11. f3 {We quickly open the center!} O-O-O 12. fxe4 dxe4 13. c3 ) 6. Nxe5 dxe4 7. Nxc6 Qg5 {The most critical and fighting move in the d5
complex. The queen hits b5, g2, and guards over h5 checks.} ( 7... bxc6 8. Bxc6+ Bd7 9. Qh5+ Ke7 10. Qe5+ Be6 ( 10... Kf7 11. Bd5+ Kg6 12. Bxe4+ ) 11. Bxa8 Qxa8 12. Qxc7+ ) ( 7... Qd5 8. c4 Qd6 {Every other move will lose on the spot to
ideas of Nd4+, or d4, or so on. On d6, Black's queen is as safe as it can be.} ( 8... Qc5 9. d4 exd3 10. Be3 ) ( 8... Qf5 9. Nd4+ ) ( 8... Qg5 9. d4 Qxg2 10. Qh5+ ) ( 8... Qd7 9. Ne5 ) 9. Nxa7+ Bd7 ( 9... c6 10. Nxc8 Rxc8 11. Ba4 ) 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Qh5+ g6 12. Qe5+ {One of the points of playing Qh5, is to expose the king
and thus force a good endgame, trading off the queens.} Kf7 13. Nb5 c6 ( 13... Re8 14. Qxc7 Qxc7 15. Nxc7 ) 14. Qd4 Qxd4 ( 14... Qe7 ) 15. Nxd4 ) 8. Qe2 {Let's
understand this position. If the Black queen leaves g5 now, we play Qh5+ and
open up the Black king and win. This means, that the Black queen is somewhat
stuck to defending h5, and thus, we threaten the move d4, where Black
struggles with the development of our pieces, and still guarding h5. They
would love to be able to meet d4 with Qxg2, and thus, they play the only
developing move defending h5 - Nf6. This hopefully explains why this is the
ONLY move for black!} Nf6 9. Nxa7+ Bd7 ( 9... Kd8 10. Nxc8 Qxg2 11. Qf1 Qxf1+ 12. Kxf1 ) 10. Bxd7+ Nxd7 11. f4 Qf5 ( 11... Qxf4 12. d4 Qf5 13. Nb5 O-O-O 14. Rf1 ) 12. Nb5 O-O-O {there are several moves white can look to play: b3, a4,
Nc3, etc. Often the king can stay in the center.} 13. b3 Bc5 14. Bb2 Rhe8 15. O-O-O {This is one solid option.} Qxf4 16. a4 c6 17. Na3 e3 18. Nc4 exd2+ 19. Qxd2 *